called Smash My Head In.

246
00:09:27.734 --> 00:09:29.194
- Close. not quite.
That's not--

247
00:09:29.277 --> 00:09:31.237
- Robby. your buddy Duke
is insisting on leaving.

248
00:09:31.321 --> 00:09:33.114
and that MVA is here.

249
00:09:33.198 --> 00:09:34.866
- Okay. I'll be right there.

250
00:09:34.949 --> 00:09:36.868
- What's open?
- Uh. South 15.

251
00:09:36.951 --> 00:09:38.203
- 78-year-old woman.

252
00:09:38.286 --> 00:09:39.913
very low speed
auto versus pedestrian

253
00:09:39.954 --> 00:09:41.414
with ground-level fall.

254
00:09:41.498 --> 00:09:42.957
Bruising on her left hip.
No head trauma.

255
00:09:43.041 --> 00:09:44.584
- Her husband.
Eddie. came along.

256
00:09:44.667 --> 00:09:46.461
- Hi. How do you do. sir?
I'm Dr. Robby. Come with us.

257
00:09:46.544 --> 00:09:48.922
We're gonna get you
set up right over here.

258
00:09:49.005 --> 00:09:50.715
- [shouts in pain]
- Sorry.

259
00:09:50.757 --> 00:09:52.425
We'll get you something
for the pain shortly.

260
00:09:52.509 --> 00:09:53.927
- Thank you.

261
00:09:53.968 --> 00:09:55.887
- Do you have
any medical problems. Frida?

262
00:09:55.970 --> 00:10:00.058
- Uh. high blood pressure.
low thyroid. um. AFib.

263
00:10:00.141 --> 00:10:02.268
- Any chest pain.
shortness of breath?

264
00:10:02.352 --> 00:10:03.937
- No.
- Front-row seat. sir.

265
00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:05.939
- So. um. what happened?

266
00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:09.275
- Well. she walked
into the car.

267
00:10:09.359 --> 00:10:11.361
- [scoffs]
You hit me.

268
00:10:11.444 --> 00:10:14.364
- No. I didn't hit you.
You hit the car.

269
00:10:14.447 --> 00:10:16.449
- You backed up right into me.

270
00:10:16.491 --> 00:10:19.119
- I wasn't even moving.
- [chuckles]

271
00:10:19.160 --> 00:10:21.454
Well. you're both
in very good hands now.

272
00:10:21.496 --> 00:10:23.248
Yes?

273
00:10:23.289 --> 00:10:26.751
- Before we get you in a gown.
we'd like to check your hip.

274
00:10:26.835 --> 00:10:28.545
- Of course.

275
00:10:30.046 --> 00:10:31.464
- I am sorry.

276
00:10:31.506 --> 00:10:33.174
We had a whole bunch
of craziness come in.

277
00:10:33.258 --> 00:10:36.136
and you got bumped down
a patient or two for CT.

278
00:10:36.177 --> 00:10:37.679
But take comfort in knowing

279
00:10:37.762 --> 00:10:39.472
it was
for some pretty nasty stuff.

280
00:10:39.514 --> 00:10:41.933
- How am I supposed
to find comfort in that

281
00:10:42.016 --> 00:10:43.810
or anything you've told me
since I got here.

282
00:10:43.893 --> 00:10:45.603
for that matter?
- I don't know.

283
00:10:45.687 --> 00:10:47.605
But everything is supposed
to come with a lesson. right?

284
00:10:47.689 --> 00:10:50.984
- Oh. this is more of your Zen
motorcycle bullshit.

285
00:10:51.025 --> 00:10:52.318
- Maybe.

286
00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:53.778
No. no. the truth is.
I'm just stalling

287
00:10:53.862 --> 00:10:55.446
'cause it's gonna be
a while longer.

288
00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:57.532
- Oh. hey. look.
I appreciate the effort.

289
00:10:57.615 --> 00:10:59.325
but you guys
are obviously jammed up.

290
00:10:59.367 --> 00:11:01.369
I'll just come back when it's
not our nation's birthday.

291
00:11:01.452 --> 00:11:02.829
- You're already here.

292
00:11:02.912 --> 00:11:04.247
It's not gonna be
that much longer. I promise.

293
00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:05.498
Just stay and get your CT.

294
00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:07.834
- I will do it all
when you get back

295
00:11:07.876 --> 00:11:09.919
and this place is less crazy.
- This place is always crazy.

296
00:11:10.003 --> 00:11:11.754
I don't know
when I'm gonna get back.

297
00:11:11.838 --> 00:11:14.174
Can you just sit the fuck down
and wait a little bit longer?

298
00:11:14.215 --> 00:11:17.385
It won't kill you.
but leaving might.

299
00:11:19.053 --> 00:11:21.347
- [sighs]

300
00:11:21.431 --> 00:11:23.600
Okay.

301
00:11:23.683 --> 00:11:25.185
No problem.

302
00:11:25.226 --> 00:11:26.728
- Thank you.

303
00:11:28.229 --> 00:11:30.273
- That's a nasty bruise.

304
00:11:30.356 --> 00:11:33.985
- Do you take aspirin
or any blood thinners?

305
00:11:34.068 --> 00:11:37.197
- Uh. Eliquis for my AFib.

306
00:11:37.238 --> 00:11:39.908
- Any tenderness here?

307
00:11:39.991 --> 00:11:41.367
- No. not really.

308
00:11:41.451 --> 00:11:43.995
- Here?
- Oh. yeah. that hurts.

309
00:11:44.037 --> 00:11:46.206
- All right. 4 of. uh. morphine
and Zofran.

310
00:11:46.289 --> 00:11:49.876
- What about up here?
- Not really.

311
00:11:49.918 --> 00:11:52.378
- All right. so let's start
with labs and plain film.

312
00:11:52.462 --> 00:11:54.380
- No. CT abdomen pelvis.

313
00:11:54.464 --> 00:11:57.175
We'll get a better view of
the hip and check for bleeding.

314
00:11:57.258 --> 00:11:58.760
The Eliquis is concerning.

315
00:11:58.843 --> 00:12:01.721
- Uh. you think
she broke her hip?

316
00:12:01.804 --> 00:12:04.224
- If it's broken. you broke it.

317
00:12:04.307 --> 00:12:05.850
- Usually for a broken hip.

318
00:12:05.934 --> 00:12:08.394
the leg is shortened
and rotates out.

319
00:12:08.478 --> 00:12:10.772
but we'll just wait
for CT results.

320
00:12:17.737 --> 00:12:19.656
- Mr. Cohen...

321
00:12:19.739 --> 00:12:22.033
I know that you were checked
on scene.

322
00:12:22.116 --> 00:12:23.826
but I was wondering
if I could do

323
00:12:23.910 --> 00:12:25.411
a quick examination of you.

324
00:12:25.495 --> 00:12:27.538
- Oh. no. I'm fine.
I was in the car.

325
00:12:27.622 --> 00:12:29.374
- Just unofficially.

326
00:12:31.125 --> 00:12:33.169
- Okay.

327
00:12:33.253 --> 00:12:36.631
- Deep breath for me.
- [breathes deeply]

328
00:12:36.714 --> 00:12:38.424
- Good. Again.

329
00:12:38.466 --> 00:12:40.218
- [breathes deeply]

330
00:12:40.301 --> 00:12:42.262
- Great.
Thanks. Eddie.

331
00:12:42.303 --> 00:12:45.640
Next thing--would you mind
taking your shoes off?

332
00:12:45.723 --> 00:12:47.308
- Uh...

333
00:12:47.392 --> 00:12:48.643
what for?

334
00:12:48.726 --> 00:12:51.271
- Just being safe.

335
00:12:51.312 --> 00:12:53.064
- [groans]

336
00:12:53.147 --> 00:12:55.066
My back's not
what it used to be.

337
00:12:55.108 --> 00:12:56.359
- Let me help you.

338
00:13:00.738 --> 00:13:03.616
- I. uh. could use a pedicure.

339
00:13:03.658 --> 00:13:05.451
- You and me both.

340
00:13:05.493 --> 00:13:09.289
Dr. King. what do you think
about doing a Romberg test?

341
00:13:09.372 --> 00:13:10.915
- What is that?

342
00:13:10.957 --> 00:13:13.293
- It's a general evaluation
of balance.

343
00:13:13.334 --> 00:13:15.920
Um. can you stand up. sir?

344
00:13:16.004 --> 00:13:17.797
- Yep.
[clears throat]

345
00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:19.799
[monitor beeping rapidly]
- How are you doing. Oliver?

346
00:13:19.841 --> 00:13:21.301
- Sats are not coming up.

347
00:13:21.342 --> 00:13:23.094
- Pressure's holding
on 400 of nitro.

348
00:13:23.177 --> 00:13:25.638
Let's up the BiPAP to 20 on 10.
- We could try phlebotomy.

349
00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:27.473
Decrease the fluid burden
on the lungs.

350
00:13:27.515 --> 00:13:29.642
- Old school.
but might buy time.

351
00:13:29.684 --> 00:13:30.935
- Hemoglobin is only 9.2.

352
00:13:31.019 --> 00:13:32.478
- He's anemic
from renal failure.

353
00:13:32.520 --> 00:13:34.063
- Then he can't afford
more blood loss.

354
00:13:34.147 --> 00:13:35.815
- We need to intubate.
We're losing this war.

355
00:13:35.898 --> 00:13:37.775
- Intubation's not
a trivial matter

356
00:13:37.859 --> 00:13:39.319
for immunosuppressed patients.

357
00:13:39.402 --> 00:13:41.195
- So we just drop
a bunch of red tops?

358
00:13:41.279 --> 00:13:42.822
- No. we do the collection
on the floor

359
00:13:42.905 --> 00:13:44.824
as if he's giving blood.
- Like medieval bloodletting.

360
00:13:44.907 --> 00:13:46.659
- Essentially.
and that is something

361
00:13:46.743 --> 00:13:48.161
you should step out for. Mason.

362
00:13:48.202 --> 00:13:50.663
Casey. thank you.
- Got a good vein for a 16.

363
00:13:50.747 --> 00:13:52.498
- One donor bag. 500 cc's.

364
00:13:52.582 --> 00:13:54.208
No more.

365
00:13:54.292 --> 00:13:56.502
- [inhales deeply]

366
00:13:56.586 --> 00:13:59.047
- Okay. let it out.
- [exhales]

367
00:13:59.130 --> 00:14:01.049
- Same again.
Deep breath in.

368
00:14:01.132 --> 00:14:03.343
- [breathes deeply]

369
00:14:03.426 --> 00:14:04.969
- Great.
All done.

370
00:14:05.053 --> 00:14:08.139
- How's she doing?
- Pulse ox 100%. normal exam.

371
00:14:08.222 --> 00:14:09.974
No evidence of injury.
- Great.

372
00:14:10.016 --> 00:14:11.684
- I got way worse
from my older brothers.

373
00:14:11.726 --> 00:14:13.144
- I bet.

374
00:14:13.186 --> 00:14:16.022
- All right. I'll go. uh.
write up her chart.

375
00:14:16.064 --> 00:14:18.358
- How about we call it a day?

376
00:14:18.399 --> 00:14:20.193
- My shift isn't over.

377
00:14:20.234 --> 00:14:23.696
- This was a shift and a half
for anyone today. believe me.

378
00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:27.033
- If it's all right with you.
I'd rather stay.

379
00:14:27.075 --> 00:14:28.493
I'm not a quitter.

380
00:14:28.576 --> 00:14:30.453
- Okay. Ms. Emma. good for you.

381
00:14:30.536 --> 00:14:33.373
But stick close to Donnie for
the rest of the day. would you?

382
00:14:33.456 --> 00:14:35.124
- Sure.

383
00:14:35.208 --> 00:14:38.169
- And you also need to make
a statement to the police.

384
00:14:38.211 --> 00:14:40.546
If we don't stand up for
ourselves. no one else will.

385
00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:44.175
We're here to help.
not to be punching bags.

386
00:14:44.258 --> 00:14:45.927
- Thank you for saving me.

387
00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:48.096
- I got you. girl.

388
00:14:50.306 --> 00:14:53.351
[indistinct chatter]

389
00:14:55.853 --> 00:14:58.022
- Something wrong?
- That depends.

390
00:14:58.106 --> 00:15:00.400
Are you a four-month-old
with severe diaper rash?

391
00:15:00.441 --> 00:15:01.943
- No. I'm Dorion Cole.

392
00:15:02.026 --> 00:15:03.736
and I'm pretty sure
that I broke my collarbone.

393
00:15:03.820 --> 00:15:06.030
- Okay. we can help with that.
I'll be back.

394
00:15:06.114 --> 00:15:07.615
- Wait. wait.
Are you serious?

395
00:15:07.698 --> 00:15:09.409
Can I at least get something
for my pain?

396
00:15:09.450 --> 00:15:11.452
- Sure. Sit tight.
- [scoffs] This place sucks.

397
00:15:11.536 --> 00:15:13.413
- Tell me about it.
Try working here.

398
00:15:13.454 --> 00:15:15.039
- Boy. you're
really working hard

399
00:15:15.123 --> 00:15:16.749
to boost those
patient satisfaction scores.

400
00:15:16.833 --> 00:15:18.251
- The chart for Central 7

401
00:15:18.292 --> 00:15:19.585
doesn't match
the patient that's in there.

402
00:15:19.627 --> 00:15:21.170
- Hang in there.
We're almost over this.

403
00:15:21.254 --> 00:15:22.755
- I was over this
six hours ago.

404
00:15:22.839 --> 00:15:25.216
- Chairs is looking like
Mullaney's on St. Paddy's Day.

405
00:15:25.299 --> 00:15:27.009
They're gonna break through
the doors like zombies...

406
00:15:27.093 --> 00:15:28.094
- Incoming.
- If we don't start moving

407
00:15:28.177 --> 00:15:29.220
more of the meat back there.

408
00:15:29.303 --> 00:15:31.013
- Dante Casella. 34.

409
00:15:31.097 --> 00:15:34.016
Blunt trauma from a fireworks
explosion in a storage unit.

410
00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:35.601
A and O. good vitals.

411
00:15:35.685 --> 00:15:37.895
large scalp laceration
and bruising to the chest.

412
00:15:37.979 --> 00:15:39.230
No meds or allergies.

413
00:15:39.313 --> 00:15:40.606
- Partial
or full thickness burns?

414
00:15:40.648 --> 00:15:42.275
- No burns.
The blast launched him

415
00:15:42.316 --> 00:15:43.943
into a rolled-down
garage door frame.

416
00:15:44.026 --> 00:15:46.279
- Am I fucking dying here?
- I'm Dr. Robby.

417
00:15:46.362 --> 00:15:49.490
{\an8}This is Dr. Santos.
- What? I can't hear you.

418
00:15:49.574 --> 00:15:50.950
{\an8}- Try the other side.

419
00:15:51.033 --> 00:15:52.618
{\an8}- I'm Dr. Santos.

420
00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:54.620
{\an8}Can you hear me?
- Yeah. yeah.

421
00:15:54.704 --> 00:15:57.123
{\an8}Dante.
Lot of ringing.

422
00:15:57.206 --> 00:15:59.959
- Hey. McKay. Joy.
you're with us.

423
00:16:01.919 --> 00:16:04.464
- One. two. three.

424
00:16:04.505 --> 00:16:08.468
- [groaning]
I need. like. four doctors?

425
00:16:08.509 --> 00:16:10.636
Oh. shit. I knew it was bad.

426
00:16:10.720 --> 00:16:12.430
- This is a teaching hospital.

427
00:16:12.513 --> 00:16:14.640
You get all the extra help
you need.

428
00:16:14.724 --> 00:16:17.894
- Airway and breathing intact.

429
00:16:17.977 --> 00:16:19.645
- Good lung sliding
bilaterally.

430
00:16:19.729 --> 00:16:21.230
- [groaning]

431
00:16:21.314 --> 00:16:22.815
- Tender over the sternum--
possible fracture.

432
00:16:22.857 --> 00:16:24.442
That's your breastbone.
[machine beeps]

433
00:16:24.525 --> 00:16:27.236
- No ectopy on monitor.
- No pericardial effusion.

434
00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:29.655
The heart looks good.
- 130 over 85.

435
00:16:29.697 --> 00:16:31.949
Pulse 108. sats 98 on 2 liters.

436
00:16:32.033 --> 00:16:33.659
- Good enough for 50 of fent.

437
00:16:33.743 --> 00:16:35.620
- He soaked through
his head dressing.

438
00:16:35.703 --> 00:16:36.996
- Let's take a peek.

439
00:16:37.038 --> 00:16:38.289
- Normally. we don't deal
with scalp lacs

440
00:16:38.372 --> 00:16:39.457
on the primary survey.

441
00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:41.125
only if there's
active bleeding.

442
00:16:41.209 --> 00:16:42.502
- With blast injuries.

443
00:16:42.543 --> 00:16:44.295
the pressure wave
can transmit energy

444
00:16:44.378 --> 00:16:45.963
through the body
and cause internal damage

445
00:16:46.047 --> 00:16:48.049
even without
any external visible signs.

446
00:16:48.132 --> 00:16:49.967
especially with organs
that are air filled.

447
00:16:50.051 --> 00:16:52.220
How are we looking. Dr. Santos?
- E-FAST negative.

448
00:16:52.303 --> 00:16:55.515
No free fluid in the belly.
- [groaning]

449
00:16:55.556 --> 00:16:58.184
{\an8}- Fuck me.
- What--what is it?

450
00:16:58.226 --> 00:17:01.187
{\an8}- It's a pretty big flap.
Checking for bleeding source.

451
00:17:01.229 --> 00:17:04.023
- Is that through the galea?
- It is. indeed.

452
00:17:04.106 --> 00:17:06.025
- Crack my head open or what?
- Don't worry.

453
00:17:06.108 --> 00:17:08.861
Your skull is intact.
It's just a. uh. very deep cut.

454
00:17:08.903 --> 00:17:11.697
- [groans]
- Ugh.

455
00:17:11.739 --> 00:17:15.993
- Okay. we got a couple
arterioles that need control.

456
00:17:16.035 --> 00:17:18.538
- Figure-of-eight sutures?
- Dr. Santos for 800.

457
00:17:18.621 --> 00:17:20.331
- What are Raney clips. Alex?

458
00:17:20.414 --> 00:17:22.375
Quicker than sutures.
- Ding. ding. ding. ding.

459
00:17:22.458 --> 00:17:24.293
Okay. clamp those bleeders.
call for CT.

460
00:17:24.377 --> 00:17:27.630
I'll be next door. and Duke's
CT line keeps growing.

461
00:17:31.092 --> 00:17:33.010
- 500 cc's out.

462
00:17:33.094 --> 00:17:35.179
- How you doing. Oliver?
- [groans]

463
00:17:35.263 --> 00:17:36.722
- Making some progress in here.

464
00:17:36.764 --> 00:17:38.391
- Can't tell
if it was the phlebotomy

465
00:17:38.432 --> 00:17:39.684
or if the nitro
finally kicked in.

466
00:17:39.767 --> 00:17:42.061
- Oh. could have been both.

467
00:17:42.144 --> 00:17:43.896
- Potassium's high. 6.5.

468
00:17:43.980 --> 00:17:45.690
- Be expected
with the missed dialysis

469
00:17:45.773 --> 00:17:46.983
and the added heat stress.

470
00:17:47.066 --> 00:17:48.859
- He needs. uh--
- Dr. Javadi.

471
00:17:48.943 --> 00:17:50.403
- Uh. he needs insulin
and glucose

472
00:17:50.486 --> 00:17:51.862
to shift the potassium
intracellular.

473
00:17:51.946 --> 00:17:54.198
- Exactly.
Uh. 10 units. amp of D-50.

474
00:17:54.282 --> 00:17:56.576
- Start with 5 milligrams
of nebulized albuterol.

475
00:17:56.617 --> 00:17:58.619
It'll shift some potassium
and help his breathing.

476
00:17:58.703 --> 00:18:00.913
- He's at risk for arrhythmias.

477
00:18:00.955 --> 00:18:04.125
- Mm. no peaked T waves.
no QRS widening.

478
00:18:04.208 --> 00:18:06.294
Insulin puts him at risk
for hypoglycemia.

479
00:18:06.377 --> 00:18:08.546
And you tie up nurses
with frequent Accu-Cheks.

480
00:18:08.629 --> 00:18:10.131
- Dr. Al-Hashimi's right.

481
00:18:10.214 --> 00:18:11.757
The nebs will hold him over
until dialysis gets here.

482
00:18:11.799 --> 00:18:13.759
You got this?
- Mm-hmm.

483
00:18:13.843 --> 00:18:16.304
[door opens]

484
00:18:16.387 --> 00:18:18.681
All good in here?
- Yep.

485
00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:23.769
Uh. I'm gonna go give
this guy's kid an update.

486
00:18:23.853 --> 00:18:25.229
He's probably freaking out.

487
00:18:25.313 --> 00:18:28.232
Come find me if you need me.
- Uh. yep.

488
00:18:30.526 --> 00:18:32.028
- Um. hey.

489
00:18:32.111 --> 00:18:34.238
Where'd you learn
that shoe trick?

490
00:18:34.322 --> 00:18:37.783
- Oh. I did a clerkship
at NJMS senior care.

491
00:18:37.867 --> 00:18:39.910
One of the attendings
always said you can learn a lot

492
00:18:39.952 --> 00:18:41.912
about your patients
just by looking at their feet.

493
00:18:41.996 --> 00:18:43.873
[bell dings]

494
00:18:43.956 --> 00:18:45.082
- Bravo. ladies.

495
00:18:45.166 --> 00:18:48.878
Now on to the next
lucky customers.

496
00:18:48.961 --> 00:18:50.630
- Probably gonna have
to stay late

497
00:18:50.671 --> 00:18:52.298
to catch up
on all these patients.

498
00:18:52.340 --> 00:18:54.091
- Night-shift reinforcements
will be here soon.

499
00:18:54.175 --> 00:18:55.635
We're supposed to be
speeding up in the 11th hour.

500
00:18:55.718 --> 00:18:57.261
not slowing down.

501
00:18:57.345 --> 00:18:58.638
They don't call it
the final sprint for nothing.

502
00:18:58.721 --> 00:19:00.139
Chop-chop.

503
00:19:04.685 --> 00:19:07.688
- Is that the. uh. mom
of the heatstroke?

504
00:19:07.772 --> 00:19:08.981
- Yeah.

505
00:19:09.023 --> 00:19:12.652
- Do you believe
it was just an accident?

506
00:19:12.735 --> 00:19:14.153
- Does it matter?

507
00:19:14.195 --> 00:19:15.821
- As a doctor. no.

508
00:19:15.905 --> 00:19:18.449
But as a mom...

509
00:19:18.532 --> 00:19:21.327
- Sometimes I can't tell
if motherhood has made me

510
00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:24.372
more understanding
or more judgmental.

511
00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:28.501
- Dana. got a couple visitors.

512
00:19:28.542 --> 00:19:30.670
- Uh. my--my brother.
There was an explosion.

513
00:19:30.711 --> 00:19:32.505
- Hi.
My mom was in a car accident.

514
00:19:32.546 --> 00:19:34.340
- Uh. okay. Monica.
can you help these fine folks

515
00:19:34.382 --> 00:19:36.092
find their loved ones?
- Yeah.

516
00:19:36.175 --> 00:19:38.094
- And. Princess. what are you
still doing here?

517
00:19:38.177 --> 00:19:40.304
Don't you got some crazy luau
pig roast barbecue thing

518
00:19:40.388 --> 00:19:42.264
to get to?
- It's <i>lechón.</i> but. yes. I do.

519
00:19:42.348 --> 00:19:44.684
I'm gonna sneak out in a few.
- Okay. yeah. yeah.

520
00:19:44.725 --> 00:19:46.852
Go have some fun
for both of us. all right?

521
00:19:46.894 --> 00:19:49.772
- Don't stay too late.
- [scoffs] Okay.

522
00:19:49.855 --> 00:19:52.108
- [groans softly]
- Hello. Ms. Stevens.

523
00:19:52.191 --> 00:19:53.317
I'm Dr. McKay.

524
00:19:53.401 --> 00:19:55.403
How you feeling?
- Stupid...

525
00:19:55.486 --> 00:19:58.155
and really. really sore.

526
00:19:58.239 --> 00:20:01.075
- Yeah. we'll. uh. get you
something for your pain. okay?

527
00:20:01.158 --> 00:20:02.868
- [groans]

528
00:20:02.952 --> 00:20:05.871
- Your last patient
left her blanket.

529
00:20:05.955 --> 00:20:07.081
- Oh.

530
00:20:07.164 --> 00:20:09.375
Uh. yeah.

531
00:20:09.458 --> 00:20:11.419
I...

532
00:20:11.502 --> 00:20:13.003
yeah. I'll take it.

533
00:20:13.087 --> 00:20:15.339
Thanks. Esme.

534
00:20:15.423 --> 00:20:17.591
Um. I'll be right back. yeah?

535
00:20:20.803 --> 00:20:23.097
Fuck!
[sighs]

536
00:20:23.180 --> 00:20:25.349
- You good?
- Yeah. yeah.

537
00:20:25.391 --> 00:20:28.728
I'm just--I'm looking
for something to put this in.

538
00:20:28.769 --> 00:20:31.272
A. uh--a patient left it.

539
00:20:33.649 --> 00:20:36.694
She died. the. uh. cancer mom
with the two kids.

540
00:20:36.777 --> 00:20:38.904
- [sighs]
Sounds like a tough one.

541
00:20:38.988 --> 00:20:40.740
- Yeah. that one sucked.

542
00:20:40.781 --> 00:20:43.200
Seeing those two young boys
say goodbye to their mother

543
00:20:43.284 --> 00:20:45.411
was brutal.

544
00:20:45.453 --> 00:20:49.749
Just makes you want to cry.

545
00:20:49.790 --> 00:20:51.917
- You should cry.
You'll feel better.

546
00:20:51.959 --> 00:20:54.211
- I wish I could.

547
00:20:54.295 --> 00:20:58.799
No. I don't even remember
the last time I cried.

548
00:20:58.883 --> 00:21:00.926
I'm not even sure
I can anymore.

549
00:21:00.968 --> 00:21:03.095
Is that what this place
does to you?

550
00:21:03.179 --> 00:21:07.391
- We get pretty good
at shutting down our feelings.

551
00:21:07.475 --> 00:21:09.810
- Yeah. I'm a little scared

552
00:21:09.894 --> 00:21:12.146
I've shut them off for so long.

553
00:21:12.229 --> 00:21:15.733
I don't know how to turn them
back on again.

554
00:21:15.816 --> 00:21:19.403
I just wish I could cry again.
you know?

555
00:21:21.238 --> 00:21:23.574
- You want a hug?

556
00:21:23.657 --> 00:21:25.075
- God. no.

557
00:21:26.660 --> 00:21:28.245
- Your mom is stable.

558
00:21:28.329 --> 00:21:30.748
but she's still waiting
on the imaging of her hip.

559
00:21:30.831 --> 00:21:32.124
We'll know more soon.

560
00:21:32.166 --> 00:21:33.626
You can wait with your dad
in the meantime.

561
00:21:33.667 --> 00:21:34.794
- I've told him a million times

562
00:21:34.835 --> 00:21:36.545
he shouldn't be driving
anymore.

563
00:21:36.629 --> 00:21:38.964
- May I ask what their home
situation is like right now?

564
00:21:39.048 --> 00:21:41.300
- I don't know. they live
over in Squirrel Hill.

565
00:21:41.383 --> 00:21:43.302
Same house I grew up in.
just the two of them.

566
00:21:43.344 --> 00:21:45.221
- We noticed your father

567
00:21:45.304 --> 00:21:47.431
exhibiting signs
of an unsteady gait.

568
00:21:47.515 --> 00:21:50.309
along with other balance
and mobility issues.

569
00:21:50.392 --> 00:21:52.311
- He sees an internist.
neurologist.

570
00:21:52.353 --> 00:21:54.104
cardiologist.
gastroenterologist.

571
00:21:54.188 --> 00:21:56.816
He's got a whole team
of "ologists."

572
00:21:56.857 --> 00:21:58.943
Both my parents used to be
in pretty great shape.

573
00:21:59.026 --> 00:22:01.612
but lately. it's like they can
barely get up the stairs.

574
00:22:01.695 --> 00:22:03.489
Half their house
isn't accessible to them.

575
00:22:03.572 --> 00:22:05.991
- Have you looked
into assisted living options?

576
00:22:06.075 --> 00:22:09.495
- Yes. but they refuse
to even talk about it with me.

577
00:22:09.578 --> 00:22:11.831
- Mr. Cohen.
you have a visitor.

578
00:22:11.872 --> 00:22:14.166
- Care Bear.
- Dad.

579
00:22:14.208 --> 00:22:18.170
You feeling okay?
- No. I'm feeling dumb.

580
00:22:18.254 --> 00:22:20.381
- Carrie. this is Dr. King.

581
00:22:20.464 --> 00:22:22.508
who will be assisting
with your mother's care.

582
00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:24.635
I was just explaining
that the treatment

583
00:22:24.718 --> 00:22:26.178
depends on the injuries.

584
00:22:26.262 --> 00:22:28.264
but there are
complicating factors.

585
00:22:28.347 --> 00:22:30.641
We are required
to report impairments

586
00:22:30.724 --> 00:22:32.268
that might affect driving.

587
00:22:32.351 --> 00:22:34.478
and you will likely have
to take another driver's test

588
00:22:34.562 --> 00:22:35.855
to keep your license.

589
00:22:35.896 --> 00:22:37.773
- What's that got
to do with Frida?

590
00:22:37.857 --> 00:22:39.483
- Well. if the hip injury
is serious

591
00:22:39.567 --> 00:22:43.028
and you're also. uh. limited.

592
00:22:43.112 --> 00:22:44.822
then it could mean

593
00:22:44.905 --> 00:22:46.866
an "unsafe to return home"
recommendation for your wife.

594
00:22:46.949 --> 00:22:49.034
- You'd be looking
at a temporary move

595
00:22:49.118 --> 00:22:51.954
to some form of assisted living
and rehabilitation

596
00:22:52.037 --> 00:22:53.038
for Frida's care.

597
00:22:53.122 --> 00:22:55.499
- How temporary?

598
00:22:55.583 --> 00:22:57.626
- Best case.
three to six months.

599
00:22:57.710 --> 00:23:00.504
but she may never return
to the functionality she had

600
00:23:00.588 --> 00:23:02.423
prior to the injury
and recovery.

601
00:23:02.506 --> 00:23:05.676
- Okay. well. kill me now.
- See what I'm dealing with?

602
00:23:05.759 --> 00:23:08.679
Dad. you need to find somewhere
to live that is safer

603
00:23:08.762 --> 00:23:10.389
and healthier for both of you.

604
00:23:10.472 --> 00:23:13.058
- You--you know. the new
communities are not anything

605
00:23:13.142 --> 00:23:14.727
like the old. scary
nursing homes.

606
00:23:14.810 --> 00:23:16.896
They're really nice. and you
get your own apartment.

607
00:23:16.979 --> 00:23:19.064
And. um. you know. my sister
actually lives in one.

608
00:23:19.106 --> 00:23:20.399
She just loves it.

609
00:23:20.482 --> 00:23:22.568
- When the dog dies.
we can talk.

610
00:23:22.651 --> 00:23:24.236
- What if you fall?

611
00:23:24.278 --> 00:23:25.905
What if you have
a heart attack or a stroke.

612
00:23:25.946 --> 00:23:27.907
and there's no one there
to help you?

613
00:23:27.948 --> 00:23:29.783
- You worry too much.
- How can I not?

614
00:23:29.867 --> 00:23:31.827
Look what happened today.

615
00:23:31.911 --> 00:23:34.163
- Okay. we're gonna leave
you two alone.

616
00:23:34.246 --> 00:23:36.624
We'll come back
with Mrs. Cohen.

617
00:23:41.629 --> 00:23:45.049
- Hey. Robby. our scalp victim
is back from CT.

618
00:23:45.132 --> 00:23:47.176
They're prepping him now.
- Shit.

619
00:23:47.259 --> 00:23:49.011
Uh. okay.
I'm coming.

620
00:23:49.094 --> 00:23:50.930
Um...

621
00:23:51.013 --> 00:23:53.557
- Is your friend doing okay?
- He's on my flight risk radar.

622
00:23:53.599 --> 00:23:56.185
- Oh. and Dana put McKay on the
guy who attacked the new nurse.

623
00:23:56.268 --> 00:23:59.605
Is she okay?
- Physically. yes.

624
00:23:59.688 --> 00:24:02.399
I heard you had a little chat
with Langdon earlier.

625
00:24:02.483 --> 00:24:03.984
- Yeah. water under the bridge.

626
00:24:04.068 --> 00:24:05.486
- You have to figure out a way
of working with him

627
00:24:05.569 --> 00:24:07.571
now that he's back.
- Or until he relapses.

628
00:24:07.655 --> 00:24:09.114
- You're becoming
a very good doctor.

629
00:24:09.198 --> 00:24:10.824
Don't let old conflicts
get in the way.

630
00:24:10.908 --> 00:24:12.743
Speaking of which.
I want you and everybody else

631
00:24:12.826 --> 00:24:15.579
to see the trauma counselor
while I'm gone. yes?

632
00:24:15.663 --> 00:24:16.997
- Yes.
- And I asked Whitaker

633
00:24:17.081 --> 00:24:18.624
to house-sit for me
while I'm gone.

634
00:24:18.707 --> 00:24:19.959
I figured that would distract

635
00:24:20.042 --> 00:24:21.418
from the whole
farmer's widow thing.

636
00:24:21.502 --> 00:24:22.503
- Wait. what?
- Bring in the mail.

637
00:24:22.586 --> 00:24:24.254
water the plants--cool?

638
00:24:24.338 --> 00:24:26.966
- Cool. Yeah. Fine.
- That looks good.

639
00:24:27.007 --> 00:24:28.968
You can start the repair
after this one.

640
00:24:29.009 --> 00:24:30.970
- Feeling any pain. sir?

641
00:24:31.053 --> 00:24:34.139
- [groggily]
Uh. no pain. just wet.

642
00:24:34.181 --> 00:24:36.767
- You already numbed him up?
- I did.

643
00:24:36.850 --> 00:24:38.143
- 1% with epi.

644
00:24:38.227 --> 00:24:40.145
- CT back yet?
- No. not yet.

645
00:24:40.229 --> 00:24:41.939
- I watched the slices come up.

646
00:24:42.022 --> 00:24:44.608
Isolated sternal fracture.
Everything else looked normal.

647
00:24:44.692 --> 00:24:46.986
Could send him home.
but given the mechanism.

648
00:24:47.069 --> 00:24:48.779
should probably watch him
overnight.

649
00:24:48.862 --> 00:24:50.656
- I agree with Dr. Garcia.

650
00:24:50.739 --> 00:24:54.410
- I agree with Dr. Garcia. too.

651
00:24:54.493 --> 00:24:58.414
- Three-layer closure--
galea. sub-Q. skin staples.

652
00:24:58.497 --> 00:24:59.832
Enjoy the fireworks.

653
00:24:59.915 --> 00:25:01.834
And hey. if I don't see you
before you leave.

654
00:25:01.875 --> 00:25:03.419
don't forget to buy me
a souvenir.

655
00:25:03.502 --> 00:25:05.504
like a custom elk-bone-carved
hunting blade.

656
00:25:05.546 --> 00:25:07.381
- Nothing less
for my favorite butcher.

657
00:25:07.464 --> 00:25:09.383
- Aww. you're gonna make
a great ex-husband

658
00:25:09.466 --> 00:25:11.677
one day. Robinavitch.

659
00:25:13.470 --> 00:25:15.639
- Hospital's got a defense
attorney looking for Jesse.

660
00:25:15.723 --> 00:25:17.391
Probably took him
to an ICE detention center.

661
00:25:17.474 --> 00:25:19.685
Said we shouldn't hold
our breath. though.

662
00:25:19.727 --> 00:25:21.812
Whatever happened
to "we the people." huh?

663
00:25:21.895 --> 00:25:24.398
<i>[indistinct radio chatter]</i>

664
00:25:24.481 --> 00:25:26.316
Anything back
on that drunk son of a bitch

665
00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:29.153
that attacked Emma?
- Not yet.

666
00:25:29.236 --> 00:25:30.988
- Christ's sake.
- I'm making a run now.

667
00:25:31.071 --> 00:25:32.364
I'll ask.
- Yeah.

668
00:25:32.448 --> 00:25:33.532
- That's the guy
who attacked Emma?

669
00:25:33.574 --> 00:25:36.452
- Mm-hmm.
- That's intense.

670
00:25:36.535 --> 00:25:38.829
How you doing?

671
00:25:38.912 --> 00:25:40.956
- Peachy.

672
00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:42.541
- Oh. that's me.

673
00:25:42.583 --> 00:25:44.668
Hey. you did what you had to do
with that guy.

674
00:25:44.752 --> 00:25:47.337
Everything's gonna be fine.
- From your lips.

675
00:25:50.758 --> 00:25:53.010
- Box of class B
launch tubes to the van.

676
00:25:53.093 --> 00:25:55.971
Next second. kaboom!
[chuckles]

677
00:25:56.055 --> 00:26:00.017
I get launched 10. 15 feet
across the garage.

678
00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:02.895
right up into the lift track.

679
00:26:02.936 --> 00:26:05.230
Hit something hard.

680
00:26:05.314 --> 00:26:08.067
Uh. I don't really remember
the rest.

681
00:26:08.108 --> 00:26:11.570
Oh. just my brother screaming.
help. help!

682
00:26:11.612 --> 00:26:15.449
I'm lying there thinking.
oh. he must be dying.

683
00:26:15.532 --> 00:26:17.534
I guess it was me
he was screaming about.

684
00:26:17.618 --> 00:26:19.453
- Your brother is
in the family room.

685
00:26:19.536 --> 00:26:22.456
He's waiting to see you.
and he is alive and well.

686
00:26:22.539 --> 00:26:24.708
[device clicks]
- Oops.

687
00:26:24.750 --> 00:26:26.376
- "Oops"?

688
00:26:26.460 --> 00:26:28.712
What--what's oops mean?

689
00:26:28.796 --> 00:26:32.674
Hello?
- It's nothing to worry about.

690
00:26:34.093 --> 00:26:36.804
We never say "oops"
in front of a patient.

691
00:26:41.141 --> 00:26:43.102
All right. try again.

692
00:26:43.143 --> 00:26:45.104
- You sure?
- Mm-hmm.

693
00:26:45.187 --> 00:26:46.855
- Okay.

694
00:26:46.939 --> 00:26:49.274
Better.
Keep going.

695
00:26:49.358 --> 00:26:50.776
- You might want to leave
the fireworks

696
00:26:50.859 --> 00:26:52.027
to the professionals.

697
00:26:52.111 --> 00:26:53.904
- We are professionals.

698
00:26:53.987 --> 00:26:58.700
Got our official PDA consumer
license a few years back.

699
00:26:58.784 --> 00:27:01.286
Gunpowder's in my blood. man.

700
00:27:01.370 --> 00:27:03.122
Nothing like that...

701
00:27:03.163 --> 00:27:06.542
[whistling. imitates explosion]

702
00:27:06.625 --> 00:27:07.960
- [sighs]
- [chuckles]

703
00:27:08.043 --> 00:27:10.129
Ain't no fighting it.

704
00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:11.922
- Amor fati.

705
00:27:12.005 --> 00:27:14.758
- More like memento mori.

706
00:27:14.842 --> 00:27:17.344
- Tomato. tom-ah-to.

707
00:27:17.427 --> 00:27:19.138
- Am I. like. the only one

708
00:27:19.179 --> 00:27:21.181
who didn't study Latin
for med school?

709
00:27:21.265 --> 00:27:22.933
- Yep.
- Yes.

710
00:27:23.016 --> 00:27:24.977
- And finished.

711
00:27:25.018 --> 00:27:26.645
- Nicely done.

712
00:27:26.687 --> 00:27:28.605
- Can I see my brother now?
- Yep.

713
00:27:28.689 --> 00:27:30.774
- Oh. motherfucker.

714
00:27:30.858 --> 00:27:33.652
- Chest pain?
- Only when I move.

715
00:27:33.694 --> 00:27:35.320
- That would be the fracture
in your sternum.

716
00:27:35.404 --> 00:27:37.156
which we will give you
another 4 of morphine for that.

717
00:27:37.197 --> 00:27:38.490
Thank you.

718
00:27:38.574 --> 00:27:40.409
- And try no laughing
or sneezing

719
00:27:40.492 --> 00:27:41.952
for the next four weeks.

720
00:27:42.035 --> 00:27:43.662
- [chuckles. groans]

721
00:27:43.745 --> 00:27:45.289
- Mr. Haas. we're gonna
switch you over

722
00:27:45.372 --> 00:27:47.791
to a high-flow nasal oxygen
instead of the BiPAP

723
00:27:47.875 --> 00:27:49.585
and see how you do.

724
00:27:49.668 --> 00:27:51.170
- This looks promising.

725
00:27:51.211 --> 00:27:53.964
- Repeat potassium is at 6.1
with the albuterol.

726
00:27:54.047 --> 00:27:57.050
- [breathing deeply]

727
00:27:59.720 --> 00:28:02.181
[sighs]
Feeling a...

728
00:28:02.222 --> 00:28:03.891
a little better.

729
00:28:06.101 --> 00:28:08.770
Don't you ever tell your mother
about how fast you drove here.

730
00:28:08.854 --> 00:28:11.356
- I thought you were gonna die.

731
00:28:11.440 --> 00:28:15.194
- Any longer.
and he might have. so good job.

732
00:28:15.235 --> 00:28:18.739
- Boy just got his permit
last week.

733
00:28:18.822 --> 00:28:20.324
Felt like I was living

734
00:28:20.365 --> 00:28:22.826
in one of those
"Fast and the Furious" movies.

735
00:28:22.868 --> 00:28:25.996
- [chuckles] I can't believe
Pine Ridge closed.

736
00:28:26.079 --> 00:28:27.372
When did that happen?

737
00:28:27.456 --> 00:28:29.708
- I read about it
a few months ago.

738
00:28:29.750 --> 00:28:31.418
Medicare spending cuts.

739
00:28:31.501 --> 00:28:33.587
- Are there any other
emergency rooms in the area?

740
00:28:33.670 --> 00:28:34.922
- Nope.

741
00:28:35.005 --> 00:28:36.548
It's gonna be
a long way to drive

742
00:28:36.590 --> 00:28:38.217
for folks out where we live.

743
00:28:38.300 --> 00:28:40.677
- Mr. Haas. you'll need
to stay here a few hours.

744
00:28:40.761 --> 00:28:42.012
Get you tuned up.

745
00:28:42.095 --> 00:28:45.515
- Yeah. I know the drill.

746
00:28:45.599 --> 00:28:47.643
- Hey. you know. Mason.
if you're hungry.

747
00:28:47.726 --> 00:28:49.394
we've got
a pretty good cafeteria.

748
00:28:49.436 --> 00:28:51.396
- Don't lie to him.

749
00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:53.398
- We have a cafeteria.

750
00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:55.317
- I'm just gonna stay here
with my dad.

751
00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:57.861
- Yeah. sure.

752
00:28:57.945 --> 00:28:59.988
- Thank you for saving him.

753
00:29:06.078 --> 00:29:08.247
- Are you still thinking
rural emergency medicine

754
00:29:08.288 --> 00:29:09.873
when you're done here?

755
00:29:09.957 --> 00:29:12.876
- Um. not thinking. doing.

756
00:29:12.960 --> 00:29:14.878
- God. I hope there are
still some hospitals left

757
00:29:14.962 --> 00:29:16.797
for you to work at.
- Yeah.

758
00:29:18.298 --> 00:29:19.800
- Oh!

759
00:29:19.883 --> 00:29:21.885
So the march of the walking
dead night shift begins.

760
00:29:21.927 --> 00:29:23.887
First one in. Mateo.
You get a gold star.

761
00:29:23.971 --> 00:29:25.305
- What happened in here?

762
00:29:25.389 --> 00:29:27.099
I left you guys
with a layup this morning.

763
00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:28.433
- Don't ask.

764
00:29:28.517 --> 00:29:30.602
- Speaking of layups.
what up. Dr. J?

765
00:29:30.644 --> 00:29:32.312
- Oh. right.

766
00:29:32.396 --> 00:29:35.107
That was. um. some sort of
basketball player. wasn't it?

767
00:29:35.190 --> 00:29:36.650
- Shame on you.

768
00:29:36.733 --> 00:29:38.944
Only the greatest Sixer
to ever play the game.

769
00:29:38.986 --> 00:29:41.238
- Week one of year four
of med school.

770
00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:43.282
You'll be ordering me around
before you know it.

771
00:29:43.323 --> 00:29:45.075
Gonna join the dark side
when you graduate?

772
00:29:45.158 --> 00:29:46.576
- The emergency department?

773
00:29:46.660 --> 00:29:50.038
- The night shift. baby.
It's wild.

774
00:29:50.122 --> 00:29:51.873
- Um...

775
00:29:51.957 --> 00:29:54.543
I haven't even decided what
residency I'm applying for yet.

776
00:29:54.626 --> 00:29:56.962
- You'll figure it out.
Got lots of time.

777
00:29:57.045 --> 00:29:59.589
- Tell that to my parents.

778
00:29:59.673 --> 00:30:01.925
- Dana. results are back
on your guy.

779
00:30:02.009 --> 00:30:03.385
- Give me those.

780
00:30:07.973 --> 00:30:09.933
- I-I choked her?

781
00:30:09.975 --> 00:30:12.269
No. I would never do
something like that.

782
00:30:12.352 --> 00:30:13.437
- But you did.

783
00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:16.773
[slam on window]

784
00:30:16.857 --> 00:30:20.485
Can you. uh--sorry. can you
excuse me for a minute?

785
00:30:20.569 --> 00:30:23.030
Jesus Christ. Dana.
- Read.

786
00:30:25.365 --> 00:30:27.200
What's he saying. anyway?

787
00:30:27.284 --> 00:30:29.453
- He's in a bit of shock.

788
00:30:29.494 --> 00:30:32.497
Claims he doesn't remember
anything.

789
00:30:32.539 --> 00:30:34.791
Says he was on the golf course
getting boozy.

790
00:30:34.875 --> 00:30:36.501
maybe a little too boozy.

791
00:30:36.585 --> 00:30:38.670
Things get hazy. next thing
you know. he's on the floor

792
00:30:38.712 --> 00:30:39.880
and everyone's
screaming at him.

793
00:30:39.963 --> 00:30:42.382
- How convenient.

794
00:30:42.466 --> 00:30:44.343
- Maybe it's better
for both of you

795
00:30:44.384 --> 00:30:46.553
that he doesn't remember
what happened.

796
00:30:48.597 --> 00:30:51.224
- Let me know when you're ready
to take my statement.

797
00:30:57.064 --> 00:30:58.857
- All right. well.
the good news is.

798
00:30:58.940 --> 00:31:01.777
your CT was negative
for skull fracture

799
00:31:01.860 --> 00:31:03.695
or intracranial hemorrhage.

800
00:31:03.737 --> 00:31:06.990
- You mean that's good news for
you and that blonde nurse lady.

801
00:31:07.032 --> 00:31:09.368
- But your lab results
were positive for alcohol

802
00:31:09.409 --> 00:31:10.994
and cocaine.

803
00:31:11.078 --> 00:31:12.788
- [scoffs]

804
00:31:12.871 --> 00:31:14.664
Okay. you got me.

805
00:31:14.748 --> 00:31:16.792
I did a couple
of birdie bumps on the turn.

806
00:31:16.875 --> 00:31:18.710
but we were just having fun
on the golf course.

807
00:31:18.794 --> 00:31:20.921
- Look. when alcohol
is mixed with cocaine.

808
00:31:21.004 --> 00:31:22.672
your liver produces
a metabolite

809
00:31:22.756 --> 00:31:24.091
called cocaethylene.

810
00:31:24.174 --> 00:31:26.093
- What does that
have to do with me

811
00:31:26.176 --> 00:31:29.054
allegedly doing what you said?

812
00:31:29.137 --> 00:31:30.764
- It's a psychoactive molecule

813
00:31:30.847 --> 00:31:33.100
more toxic and potent
than cocaine.

814
00:31:33.183 --> 00:31:37.396
And it can lead to confusion.
paranoia. aggression.

815
00:31:37.437 --> 00:31:40.023
and even psychosis.

816
00:31:40.065 --> 00:31:41.775
- [sighs]

817
00:31:41.858 --> 00:31:44.778
What happens now?

818
00:31:44.861 --> 00:31:47.030
- We're gonna monitor you
for a few hours.

819
00:31:47.114 --> 00:31:49.408
especially given
your likely concussion.

820
00:31:49.491 --> 00:31:50.826
And you'll need to give
a statement

821
00:31:50.909 --> 00:31:52.953
to the police outside
in the meantime.

822
00:31:58.250 --> 00:32:00.335
- Oh. you lucky
this was just a poke.

823
00:32:00.419 --> 00:32:01.503
Spared the muscle.

824
00:32:01.586 --> 00:32:03.088
- See?
It could have been worse.

825
00:32:03.171 --> 00:32:04.714
- No shit. Sherman.

826
00:32:04.798 --> 00:32:06.758
The triangular bayonets
they created back then

827
00:32:06.800 --> 00:32:08.093
were designed to leave wounds

828
00:32:08.135 --> 00:32:10.053
that are nearly impossible
to stitch.

829
00:32:10.137 --> 00:32:12.431
- Those bayonets
had never met me.

830
00:32:12.472 --> 00:32:14.057
- Oh. wow.
- What?

831
00:32:14.141 --> 00:32:15.851
- It's all good.
We got it covered.

832
00:32:15.934 --> 00:32:19.104
- No. are you guys
from the Fort Pitt Museum?

833
00:32:19.187 --> 00:32:21.440
- Yeah. You familiar?
- Yeah.

834
00:32:21.481 --> 00:32:22.816
I love you guys.

835
00:32:22.899 --> 00:32:24.317
My mom would take me
to the fort

836
00:32:24.401 --> 00:32:25.986
every time we'd come down
to visit family as a kid.

837
00:32:26.069 --> 00:32:28.113
- We've been volunteering there
as living historians

838
00:32:28.155 --> 00:32:30.449
for over 20 years.
- I probably saw you then.

839
00:32:30.532 --> 00:32:32.993
Man. I can't wait to tell
my parents about this.

840
00:32:33.076 --> 00:32:34.744
- Getting stabbed
must have been scary.

841
00:32:34.828 --> 00:32:37.247
- Yeah. well. Poindexter here
stumbled over his boots

842
00:32:37.330 --> 00:32:38.957
and nearly impaled me.

843
00:32:38.999 --> 00:32:40.625
- Wouldn't have mattered if you
weren't out of formation.

844
00:32:40.667 --> 00:32:41.960
- You're in good hands.

845
00:32:42.002 --> 00:32:43.837
This guy could have saved
a lot of lives

846
00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:46.631
with his sutures back in 1776.

847
00:32:46.715 --> 00:32:49.926
- I was not out of formation.
- You were out of formation.

848
00:32:50.010 --> 00:32:51.344
- Hi. again.

849
00:32:51.428 --> 00:32:53.096
Good news. Mrs. Cohen.

850
00:32:53.138 --> 00:32:55.891
Your imaging results
show no hip fracture

851
00:32:55.974 --> 00:32:57.976
and no internal bleeding.

852
00:32:58.018 --> 00:33:00.103
But you do have
a small hairline fracture

853
00:33:00.187 --> 00:33:01.771
of the superior pubic ramus.

854
00:33:01.855 --> 00:33:03.773
- Well.
that doesn't sound good.

855
00:33:03.857 --> 00:33:04.983
- Well. if you're gonna
have a fracture.

856
00:33:05.025 --> 00:33:06.234
it's the best one to have.

857
00:33:06.318 --> 00:33:08.653
- Do I need to stay
in the hospital?

858
00:33:08.737 --> 00:33:09.821
- Not necessarily.

859
00:33:09.863 --> 00:33:11.448
Your recovery should be

860
00:33:11.531 --> 00:33:13.450
pretty straightforward
if we can control your pain.

861
00:33:13.533 --> 00:33:15.994
But you need to take it easy
and stay off your feet

862
00:33:16.077 --> 00:33:17.829
for six to eight weeks.

863
00:33:17.871 --> 00:33:19.581
- How can she go home
if she can't walk?

864
00:33:19.664 --> 00:33:22.083
- Oh. she can bear weight
and walk with some help.

865
00:33:22.167 --> 00:33:25.003
And we'll get you a walker
and schedule physical therapy.

866
00:33:25.045 --> 00:33:28.673
{\an8}- So--so we can go home.
- [laughing] Yes.

867
00:33:28.757 --> 00:33:31.510
{\an8}- Dad. you can't take care
of Mom all by yourself.

868
00:33:31.551 --> 00:33:33.678
{\an8}- Oh. we'll manage.

869
00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:36.014
{\an8}- You guys. you need
to be realistic.

870
00:33:36.056 --> 00:33:39.017
- I don't want strangers
hanging around in the house.

871
00:33:39.059 --> 00:33:40.894
- It's not strangers.
It's helpers.

872
00:33:40.977 --> 00:33:42.687
- Mm-mm. no.
No. thanks.

873
00:33:42.729 --> 00:33:44.898
- Mm-mm.
- Doctors. please.

874
00:33:46.566 --> 00:33:48.527
- I am worried
about your ability

875
00:33:48.568 --> 00:33:51.363
to get the assistance
you need. Mrs. Cohen.

876
00:33:51.446 --> 00:33:53.740
It may be time to think about
some of those

877
00:33:53.823 --> 00:33:57.619
alternative living options
we mentioned.

878
00:33:57.702 --> 00:33:59.371
- I can take care of her.

879
00:33:59.412 --> 00:34:01.623
- Dad. are you gonna be able
to get her into the bathroom

880
00:34:01.706 --> 00:34:03.500
onto the toilet
in the middle of the night?

881
00:34:03.583 --> 00:34:05.544
Are you gonna help her change
her clothes in the morning?

882
00:34:05.585 --> 00:34:07.295
Are you gonna--
- We're--we're fine.

883
00:34:07.379 --> 00:34:10.966
- Dad. please just try it.

884
00:34:11.049 --> 00:34:12.884
You don't have to sell
the house right away.

885
00:34:12.926 --> 00:34:16.054
Just see if you like it.

886
00:34:16.137 --> 00:34:18.557
- You could move in with us.
- No. I can't.

887
00:34:18.598 --> 00:34:20.183
I have work. I have the kids.
I can't.

888
00:34:20.267 --> 00:34:22.143
- No. No. No.

889
00:34:22.227 --> 00:34:24.437
No. Okay?
Just no.

890
00:34:26.439 --> 00:34:29.609
- Carrie. could I speak
with you outside for a minute?

891
00:34:32.779 --> 00:34:34.573
[door opens]

892
00:34:37.284 --> 00:34:38.910
- It's like that every time.

893
00:34:38.994 --> 00:34:40.579
- It's tough to find
the balance

894
00:34:40.662 --> 00:34:42.747
between respecting your
loved ones' needs for agency

895
00:34:42.831 --> 00:34:45.417
and doing what's best
for their safety.

896
00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:48.920
I was wondering if you had
your parents' medication lists

897
00:34:49.004 --> 00:34:51.923
with you or on your phone.
- Yeah.

898
00:34:52.007 --> 00:34:55.260
- I'd like to take a quick
look at it. if that's okay.

899
00:34:55.343 --> 00:34:56.886
- Yeah.

900
00:34:58.847 --> 00:35:00.849
- My man. how you doing?

901
00:35:00.932 --> 00:35:02.100
- Like you better roll in

902
00:35:02.183 --> 00:35:04.102
a bar cart
and a happy hour buffet

903
00:35:04.144 --> 00:35:06.187
if I'm gonna be stuck
in this place much longer.

904
00:35:06.271 --> 00:35:07.606
- This place is a traffic jam.

905
00:35:07.647 --> 00:35:08.940
We're trying to merge you in.
I promise.

906
00:35:09.024 --> 00:35:10.233
- That's no traffic jam.

907
00:35:10.317 --> 00:35:11.776
That's a 20-car pileup.

908
00:35:11.818 --> 00:35:13.778
- The sooner you get out.
the sooner I get out.

909
00:35:13.862 --> 00:35:17.115
so you know
I'm not bullshitting you.

910
00:35:17.157 --> 00:35:19.034
- Why are you jonesing
so hard to get out

911
00:35:19.117 --> 00:35:20.785
and start your ride tonight?

912
00:35:20.869 --> 00:35:22.579
- I've got a schedule.

913
00:35:22.662 --> 00:35:25.540
I've got places to go.
I've got people to see.

914
00:35:29.586 --> 00:35:32.672
I just have to get going.

915
00:35:32.756 --> 00:35:34.758
- You're worried
if you don't leave tonight.

916
00:35:34.841 --> 00:35:37.135
you won't leave at all.

917
00:35:37.177 --> 00:35:39.304
[sighs]
Look. I get it.

918
00:35:39.346 --> 00:35:42.432
I can feel it in the air here.
This place is like quicksand.

919
00:35:42.515 --> 00:35:45.268
- [breathes deeply]
Right.

920
00:35:45.352 --> 00:35:47.020
[clears throat]
- Dr. Robby?

921
00:35:47.103 --> 00:35:51.149
Uh. Dante. the fireworks guy--
something's wrong.

922
00:35:51.191 --> 00:35:52.817
- Okay. shit.
- [sighs]

923
00:35:52.901 --> 00:35:54.653
- Um. do not go anywhere.
You are next up.

924
00:35:54.736 --> 00:35:56.279
I'm gonna deliver you myself.

925
00:35:56.363 --> 00:35:58.198
- I'm starting to feel like
a hostage in this place.

926
00:35:58.281 --> 00:36:00.158
- How do you think I feel?

927
00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:03.244
[indistinct chatter]

928
00:36:06.373 --> 00:36:09.417
[phone ringing]

929
00:36:12.921 --> 00:36:15.006
[monitor beeping rapidly]

930
00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:17.842
What's going on?
- Fucking chest hurts.

931
00:36:17.926 --> 00:36:21.012
[wheezing]
- Systolic's down to 78.

932
00:36:21.096 --> 00:36:23.014
- Blood loss from scalp lac?
- Uh. that's highly unlikely.

933
00:36:23.098 --> 00:36:24.849
Dr. Santos?
- Good breath sounds.

934
00:36:24.933 --> 00:36:27.185
But neck veins are up.
Checking the heart now.

935
00:36:27.227 --> 00:36:29.688
- Okay. 500-cc bolus.
100% non-rebreather please.

936
00:36:29.729 --> 00:36:32.315
- Okay. pericardial effusion.
RV collapse--it's tamponade.

937
00:36:32.399 --> 00:36:34.192
- Yeah. let's prep
for a pericardiocentesis.

938
00:36:34.275 --> 00:36:36.361
- What's going on?
Is he gonna be okay?

939
00:36:36.444 --> 00:36:38.863
You said he was fine.
- CT scan was normal.

940
00:36:38.947 --> 00:36:40.824
- Things change.

941
00:36:40.865 --> 00:36:44.202
- Dante. there is a collection
of blood around your heart.

942
00:36:44.285 --> 00:36:46.663
We need to drain it.
- Oh. fuck.

943
00:36:46.746 --> 00:36:48.873
- Okay. 0.5 per kilo
ketamine. please.

944
00:36:48.915 --> 00:36:50.542
- Won't that drop
his pressure even more?

945
00:36:50.583 --> 00:36:51.835
- We don't have a choice.

946
00:36:51.918 --> 00:36:53.878
We cannot do this
on a moving target.

947
00:36:53.962 --> 00:36:56.339
- Dante. Jesus fucking Christ.
It's my baby brother.

948
00:36:56.423 --> 00:36:58.508
- Hey. Perlah?
- Sir. I'm so sorry.

949
00:36:58.591 --> 00:37:00.051
but you can't
be in here right now.

950
00:37:00.135 --> 00:37:01.803
- What's wrong with him?
Hey. Dante. Dante.

951
00:37:01.886 --> 00:37:04.472
Hey. just hear me--
- Okay. I'm so sorry.

952
00:37:04.556 --> 00:37:06.057
You can't be in there
right now. okay?

953
00:37:06.141 --> 00:37:07.726
We have to stabilize.
- They said he was fine.

954
00:37:07.809 --> 00:37:09.310
- Yeah. Okay.
There's been a complication.

955
00:37:09.394 --> 00:37:11.146
I just need you to take
a couple deep breaths

956
00:37:11.229 --> 00:37:12.814
and try to stay calm.
- Please. Please.

957
00:37:12.897 --> 00:37:15.734
- Okay. just breathe with me.
In. Okay. out.

958
00:37:15.775 --> 00:37:17.527
Look at me.
Breathe in.

959
00:37:17.610 --> 00:37:19.362
- [breathes deeply]
- Out.

960
00:37:19.446 --> 00:37:21.740
Very good.
In. out.

961
00:37:21.823 --> 00:37:24.284
Okay. stay calm. okay?
We got this.

962
00:37:27.120 --> 00:37:28.747
- I can't leave
you <i>pendejos</i> alone.

963
00:37:28.788 --> 00:37:30.415
- Tamponade with shock.
- From what?

964
00:37:30.457 --> 00:37:31.958
- Uh. I'm guessing a small tear

965
00:37:32.041 --> 00:37:33.626
in the right atrium
from the sternal fracture.

966
00:37:33.710 --> 00:37:34.961
- If it was ventricular.

967
00:37:35.044 --> 00:37:36.546
he would have crashed
in the field.

968
00:37:36.629 --> 00:37:38.298
I'll call cardiothoracic.
See if they have an OR.

969
00:37:38.381 --> 00:37:39.883
- Systolic's down to 64.

970
00:37:39.924 --> 00:37:41.217
- Okay. have you ever done
an apical approach?

971
00:37:41.301 --> 00:37:43.595
- Nope.
- No time like the present.

972
00:37:43.678 --> 00:37:45.722
Go lateral to my probe.
- Why not subcostal?

973
00:37:45.805 --> 00:37:48.600
- This is a shorter distance.
There are fewer structures.

974
00:37:48.683 --> 00:37:49.976
If you can see fluid.
there's nothing

975
00:37:50.059 --> 00:37:52.103
between the probe
and the pericardial.

976
00:37:52.145 --> 00:37:54.272
- There? There.
the needle's in the effusion.

977
00:37:54.314 --> 00:37:57.609
- Mm-hmm. Draw back.
- Good blood return.

978
00:37:57.692 --> 00:37:59.486
- Okay. sometimes it only takes
20 cc's

979
00:37:59.569 --> 00:38:01.237
to let that heart fill again.

980
00:38:01.321 --> 00:38:04.115
- Carotid pulse much stronger.
- Thanks. Be right up.

981
00:38:04.157 --> 00:38:05.784
They'll have a room
